ions can not be entangled by them either. This is\nnot a foregone conclusion per se (since Gaussian bound entangled states do\nexist) and settles a question that had been left unanswered in the existing\nliterature on the subject. This paper, enjoyable by both the quantum optics and\nthe matrix analysis communities, overall delivers technical and conceptual\nadvances which are likely to be useful for further applications in continuous\nvariable quantum information theory, beyond the separability problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Dec 2016 20:05:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 12 Jun 2017 17:47:39 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 21 Feb 2018 14:07:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-22"}
